## Quantifying Vaccine Effectiveness and Examples

### Mathematical Expression

Vaccine effectiveness (VE) can be calculated using the odds ratio (OR) of infection among vaccinated versus unvaccinated individuals:

\[
VE = (1 - OR) \times 100
\]

This formula expresses the percentage reduction in disease risk among vaccinated individuals compared to unvaccinated ones ([News-Medical, 2021](https://www.news-medical.net/health/Vaccine-Effectiveness.aspx)).

### Examples of Vaccine Effectiveness

| Vaccine               | Typical Effectiveness Rate (%) | Notes                                                                                   |
|-----------------------|-------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Measles (MMR)         | Up to 99                      | One of the most effective vaccines; provides strong and long-lasting immunity           |
| Mumps (MMR)           | ~88                           | Slightly lower effectiveness compared to measles                                       |
| Rubella (MMR)         | ~97                           | High effectiveness                                                                      |
| Influenza (Flu Shot)  | 20–60                         | Varies annually due to viral mutations and vaccine strain match                         |
| COVID-19 (mRNA vaccines) | 90–95 (efficacy in trials)    | Real-world effectiveness varies; strong protection against severe disease persists      |
| Whooping Cough (Pertussis) | 80 initially, drops to 60 after 4 years | Waning immunity necessitates booster doses                                              |

This table illustrates that while some vaccines approach near-complete protection, none achieve absolute (100%) effectiveness ([Medical News Today, 2021](https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/what-is-vaccine-efficacy); [Daily Mail, 2020](https://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-9002315/Why-no-vaccine-100-effective.html)).

