## The FDA Threshold and Public Health Implications

The U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) sets a minimum effectiveness threshold of 50% for COVID-19 vaccines to receive approval or emergency use authorization. This standard acknowledges that while vaccines may not be perfect, they provide substantial protection that benefits both individuals and communities ([Health Desk, 2021](https://health-desk.org/articles/can-vaccines-be-100-effective-against-covid-19-or-any-other-illnesses)).

Vaccination reduces disease transmission, severity, hospitalizations, and deaths, even when breakthrough infections occur. High vaccination coverage also contributes to herd immunity, limiting virus circulation and protecting vulnerable populations ([VaccinesToday, 2021](https://www.vaccinestoday.eu/stories/why-do-some-vaccinated-kids-still-get-sick/)).

---

## Addressing Misconceptions: Why Some Vaccinated Individuals Still Get Sick

A common misconception is that vaccines failing to provide 100% protection means they are ineffective. However, even highly effective vaccines cannot guarantee immunity for every individual due to the factors discussed.

For example, during an outbreak, the absolute number of vaccinated individuals who get sick may exceed unvaccinated cases simply because the vaccinated population is larger. This does not imply vaccine failure but reflects population dynamics ([VaccinesToday, 2021](https://www.vaccinestoday.eu/stories/why-do-some-vaccinated-kids-still-get-sick/)).

Additionally, vaccines often reduce disease severity, meaning vaccinated individuals who contract the disease are less likely to experience severe outcomes, hospitalization, or death ([OSF HealthCare, 2022](https://www.osfhealthcare.org/blog/vaccine-efficacy-explained/)).

---

## Summary and Conclusion

Based on the comprehensive review of scientific literature and expert analyses, the following conclusions can be drawn:

- **No vaccine is 100% effective.** This is due to biological variability in immune responses, pathogen mutations, vaccine handling issues, and population factors.

- **Vaccine efficacy measured in clinical trials tends to be higher than effectiveness observed in real-world settings.** Clinical trials represent ideal conditions, while effectiveness accounts for practical challenges.

- **Despite not being perfect, vaccines provide substantial protection against disease, especially severe illness and death.** For example, COVID-19 vaccines with 90-95% efficacy have significantly reduced hospitalizations and fatalities worldwide.

- **Vaccination remains critical for individual and public health.** High vaccination rates contribute to herd immunity, reducing disease spread and protecting vulnerable groups.

- **Understanding the difference between efficacy and effectiveness helps manage expectations and supports informed decision-making.**

In conclusion, while vaccines are not 100% effective, their benefits far outweigh their limitations. They remain a cornerstone of infectious disease control and prevention, saving millions of lives annually.

